From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Entrpi <entrpi@proton.me>
Date: Sun, 8 Feb 2026 21:44:46 +1100
Subject: [PATCH] PCI: sky1: Switch ACPI from MCFG quirk to vendor scan handler
 approach

Replace the MCFG quirk + companion driver approach with the vendor
kernel's pattern: block PNP0A08 root bridges with an ACPI scan handler
and let pci-sky1.c probe CIXH2020 platform devices directly. This gives
the full init sequence (PHY, reset, GPIO, straps, controller registers,
link training) identical to DT boot.

The MCFG quirk approach could not replicate the full driver init
sequence, so link training failed for some controllers (notably WiFi).

ACPI scan handler (pci-sky1-acpi.c):
- Block PNP0A08 on Sky1 (detected via MCFG OEM ID)
- Create CIXH2020 platform devices with filtered _CRS resources
  (exclude DWordMemory/DWordIO address windows that exceed ARM64's
  IO_SPACE_LIMIT)
- Platform devices created WITHOUT fwnode to bypass fw_devlink
  (ACPI _DSD reference chain CIXHA010->CIXH2023->CIXH2020 has no
  clock controller driver, causing permanent deferred probe)
- ACPI device passed via platform_data for probe-time companion setup

pci-sky1.c ACPI adaptations:
- Set ACPI_COMPANION from platform_data at probe start
- Index-based resource/IRQ lookup (ACPI _CRS is unnamed)
- Optional clocks and resets (firmware-managed under ACPI)
- ACPI GPIO mapping for PERST# from _CRS GpioIo
- device_property_read_bool() for firmware-agnostic properties

Supporting changes:
- pinctrl-sky1: Accept ACPI boot (firmware handles pin muxing)
- phy-cix-pcie: Skip OF provider under ACPI (use lookup tables)
- Remove MCFG quirk, sky1_pcie_ecam_ops, CIXH2020 forbidden_id_list
  entry, and pci_acpi_cadence_sky1_fixups()
